readiness.insight: Based on your partially ready rating, your current fitness level and activity suggest that you have some ground to cover before attempting Freel Peak. Freel Peak is rated with a climbing difficulty of 72 out of 100, which is quite challenging. Although your VO2 max indicates a moderate level of cardio fitness, your sedentary activity level and lack of regular exercise mean that your overall endurance and stamina might not be sufficient for such a demanding climb. To prepare for this climb, consider incorporating regular cardio exercises such as running or cycling into your routine to build stamina. Increase your weekly activity gradually, aiming for at least 150 minutes of moderate aerobic exercise per week, as recommended. Complement your cardio training with strength exercises targeting your legs and core to improve your climbing efficiency and reduce the risk of injury. Additionally, ensure you maintain a balanced diet rich in carbohydrates, proteins, and healthy fats to fuel your workouts and recovery. Gradually acclimate to altitude by planning a shorter, easier climb before attempting Freel Peak to prepare your body for the elevation changes. Consulting with a fitness professional can provide personalized guidance tailored to your progress and needs.
